{"title":"S3-DST: Structured Open-Domain Dialogue Segmentation and State Tracking in the Era of LLMs","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Open-domain LLM chats are long, multi-intent, and multi-topic, making traditional turn-level DST in narrow domains inadequate; we need a zero-shot way to jointly detect topical segments and track intent/state per segment.","method":"S3-DST introduces a structured prompting framework that performs joint segmentation and state tracking with no training. It uses hierarchical XML for both inputs and outputs, encoding each turn inside <T{id}> with nested tags for user/agent and labels. A per-turn preceding_topical_relation (YES/NO) marks segment boundaries and enforces that all turns within a segment share the same intent and domain. Valid categories are provided in-advance in XML, constraining generation and enabling reliable parsing; empirically this yields higher intent/domain JGA and segmentation accuracy than zero-shot baselines."},{"problem":"LLMs struggle to maintain and ground long conversational context, leading to errors and degradation as dialogues get longer.","method":"Pre-Analytical Recollection (PAR) is a grounding strategy that first requires the model to summarize each turn in ≤3 sentences within a <summary> tag before emitting segmentation and state labels. PAR is akin to chain-of-thought but explicitly grounds predictions to the referenced turn content, improving long-context tracking. Ablations show removing PAR notably hurts JGA, especially in longer conversations, confirming its role in mitigating performance drop with increasing dialogue length."},{"problem":"On standard task-oriented DST benchmarks, zero-shot LLMs inconsistently extract and update slot values over turns without explicit structure or conflict resolution.","method":"S3-DST adapts its structured prompting to MWOZ by prompting an XML-structured, per-turn template that echoes the agent/user utterances and outputs an updated list of ['SLOT-value'] tags drawn from a predefined <slots> list (with <valid_values> when applicable). The prompt instructs deduplication and conflict resolution by keeping the most recent user-provided value and to use dontcare only when explicitly stated. This zero-shot, structured extraction achieves state-of-the-art zero-shot JGA on MWOZ 2.1/2.4 compared to strong LLM baselines."}]}
